const t="https://openkotor.com/schemas/binary-format.schema.json",e="TLK",n=`TLK (Talk Table) files store the game's dialogue and other localized text in KotOR I & II. Each string has an index (0 to stringCount−1); scripts, GFF fields, and SSF files refer to strings by this index. dialog.tlk is the main talk table; other TLK files may be used for specific modules or sounds.

Layout: a 20-byte header (magic "TLK ", version, language ID, string count, and the file offset where the string data block starts). Immediately after the header comes the string entry table: stringCount entries of 40 bytes each. Each entry describes one string: flags, optional sound resref (for voice), volume/pitch variance, and—relative to the string data block—the offset and length of the text. The string data block starts at stringEntriesOffset and holds all string texts; entry i's text is at (stringEntriesOffset + entry[i].stringOffset) and is entry[i].stringLength bytes.

Parsing: Read the header (20 bytes). The entry table starts at offset 20 and is stringCount × 40 bytes. For each index i, read StringEntry at 20 + i×40. To get the text for string i: fileOffset = stringEntriesOffset + entry[i].stringOffset; read entry[i].stringLength bytes at fileOffset (trim trailing nulls for display). SoundResRef is the voice filename (null-padded 16 chars) when the entry has sound; otherwise empty.

Writing: Build the entry table (flags, soundResRef, volumeVariance, pitchVariance, stringOffset relative to the start of the string data block, stringLength, soundLength). Concatenate all string texts into the string data block and set each entry's stringOffset and stringLength. Write header (stringEntriesOffset = 20 + stringCount×40), then the entry table, then the string data. All multi-byte integers are little-endian.`,s="little",i="windows-1252",r="Header",a={Header:{kind:"struct",description:'20 bytes at the start. fileType is "TLK ", fileVersion is the format version. languageID identifies the language (see LanguageId in ERF/GFF for the same enum). stringCount is how many strings are in the table; the entry table has that many 40-byte entries starting at offset 20. stringEntriesOffset is the file offset where the string data block begins (typically 20 + stringCount×40).',fields:[{name:"fileType",type:{kind:"string",length:4},description:"Must be 'TLK ' (4 chars, space-padded)."},{name:"fileVersion",type:{kind:"string",length:4},description:"Format version string."},{name:"languageId",type:"u32",description:"Language ID (e.g. 0 = English). Same values as in ERF/GFF LanguageId."},{name:"stringCount",type:"u32",description:"Number of strings. Entry table size = stringCount × 40 bytes, starting at offset 20."},{name:"stringEntriesOffset",type:"u32",description:"File offset where the string data block starts. String text for entry i is at (stringEntriesOffset + entry[i].stringOffset), length entry[i].stringLength."}]},StringEntry:{kind:"struct",description:"One string entry (40 bytes). Describes a single TLK string by index: flags (e.g. has sound), optional sound resref (voice filename, 16 chars null-padded—trim for display), volume and pitch variance for playback, and the position of the text in the string data block. stringOffset is relative to the start of the string data block (header.stringEntriesOffset); the actual file offset is stringEntriesOffset + stringOffset. stringLength is how many bytes of text to read (trim trailing nulls when displaying). soundLength is the duration or length of the associated sound; used by the engine.",fields:[{name:"flags",type:"u32",description:"Flags (e.g. bit for has sound)."},{name:"soundResRef",type:{kind:"string",length:16},description:"Voice/sound filename when present, null-padded to 16 chars. Trim trailing nulls."},{name:"volumeVariance",type:"u32",description:"Volume variance for sound playback."},{name:"pitchVariance",type:"u32",description:"Pitch variance for sound playback."},{name:"stringOffset",type:"u32",description:"Offset into the string data block (relative to stringEntriesOffset) where this string's text starts."},{name:"stringLength",type:"u32",description:"Length of this string's text in bytes. Read this many bytes at (stringEntriesOffset + stringOffset)."},{name:"soundLength",type:"u32",description:"Sound length/duration; used by the engine."}]}},o={headerSize:20,stringEntrySize:40},g=[{name:"header",typeRef:"Header",offset:0,size:20,description:"Fixed 20-byte header. Read to get languageId, stringCount, and stringEntriesOffset. The entry table follows at offset 20."},{name:"stringEntryTable",typeRef:"StringEntry",offset:20,size:"stringCount * 40",description:"String entry table: stringCount entries, 40 bytes each. Entry i is at offset 20 + i×40. Each entry gives flags, soundResRef, volumeVariance, pitchVariance, stringOffset (relative to string data block), stringLength, and soundLength. To get the text for string i: fileOffset = stringEntriesOffset + entry[i].stringOffset; read entry[i].stringLength bytes at fileOffset."},{name:"stringData",offset:"stringEntriesOffset",size:0,description:"String data block. All string texts are stored here; each entry in the string entry table points into this block via stringOffset (relative) and stringLength. No length field for the block—it runs until the end of the file or until the next known structure. To read string i: use entry[i].stringOffset and entry[i].stringLength; seek to (stringEntriesOffset + stringOffset) and read stringLength bytes (typically trim trailing nulls for display)."}],f={$schema:t,name:e,description:n,endianness:s,encoding:i,root:r,types:a,constants:o,sections:g};export{t as $schema,o as constants,f as default,n as description,i as encoding,s as endianness,e as name,r as root,g as sections,a as types};
